# Java & Spring Boot Standards

## Language (JDK 25)

- Prefer **modern Java** where it fits: **records**, **pattern matching** (`switch`, `instanceof`), **sealed classes** when modeling closed hierarchies.
- Match the JDK in `pom.xml` (`java.version`); this repo uses **JDK 25** for language and bytecode.

## Data & events

- Prefer **`record`** over mutable classes for **DTOs**, **Kafka event** payloads, and small immutable value types.
- Keep records **focused**; avoid embedding behavior that belongs in a domain service.

## Spring

- Use **constructor injection** only (`@Service`, `@Component`, `@Configuration` with final fields + single constructor). **Do not** use `@Autowired` on fields.
- Prefer **`var`** for **local** variables when the type is obvious from the right-hand side (readability).

## Logging & boilerplate

- **Do not use Lombok** (`@Slf4j`, `@Data`, etc.). Use an explicit **SLF4J** logger: `private static final Logger log = LoggerFactory.getLogger(MyClass.class);`
- Use **explicit constructors** (or compact canonical constructors on records) instead of Lombok-generated code.

## Structure

- Follow **Clean Code**: **small methods**, **single responsibility**, names that state intent.
- Extract helpers when a method does more than one clear thing; avoid “god” services and mega-classes.
